ore native-image behavior for a newer version while preserving existing dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:53:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:55:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - If metadata fixes make the native run pass but the dynamic-access ratio drops, ask for restored coverage first. Passing native execution is not enough by itself.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:66:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:68:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:106:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-java-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR described as `fixes-java-run-fail` or one that fixes Java/JVM runtime test failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the Java runtime fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair tests, dependencies, or narrow runtime setup after an existing library version compiles, but the JVM-based test fails when it runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library already exists, so the goal is to restore Java runtime behavior for the new version while preserving meaningful test and dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:54:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:66:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:68:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:106:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-javac-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes Java compilation failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the compile fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:20:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:52:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:54:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:55:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:64:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:66:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:103:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/README.md:27:It covers compile-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the compile fix, preserve meaningful tests, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:32:It covers JVM runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the Java runtime fix, preserve meaningful tests and assertions, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:37:It covers native-image runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: verify the native path is fixed rather than skipped, keep metadata and test changes scoped, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:21:- Require at least 50% reported dynamic-access coverage when there are dynamic-access calls to cover. Use the exploded stats files under `stats/<group>/<artifact>/<metadata-version>/stats.json` when available, and block the PR when dynamic-access coverage is below 50% or the PR provides no credible dynamic-access coverage evidence for non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:22:- Treat dynamic-access coverage counts as a minimum gate, not complete metadata evidence. They can miss metadata required through downstream libraries, so do not use high coverage alone to prove that the submitted metadata is complete or necessary.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:23:- Treat `0/0` dynamic-access coverage as a valid no-calls case, not as failed coverage. Do not reject a PR only because the exploded stats report `0/0` dynamic-access calls while the PR adds metadata; those stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:24:- Do not explicitly read or review individual metadata entries. Use the metadata entry count reported in the PR description for the metadata/dynamic-access mismatch check; do not manually count entries from metadata files. Only request investigation when the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:56:   - For metadata/dynamic-access mismatch checks, use only the metadata entry count reported in the PR description, such as `Entries` or `Entries found`; do not manually count metadata entries from files.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:62:   - Confirm reported dynamic-access coverage is at least 50% when the stats include dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:63:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls and `reachability-metadata.json` is `{}`, that is acceptable as long as the test is library-specific and the scope is otherwise correct.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:64:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls while adding metadata, do not reject it on that basis alone; dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:65:   - If the stats report less than 50% coverage for non-zero dynamic-access calls, or no usable coverage signal for claimed dynamic-access behavior, ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:66:   - Ask for metadata/coverage mismatch investigation only when the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:89:  - Reported dynamic-access coverage is below 50% for non-zero dynamic-access calls, absent for claimed dynamic-access behavior, or not credible from the diff.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:99:- For insufficient dynamic-access coverage: say that new-library PRs need at least 50% dynamic-access coverage when there are dynamic-access calls to cover, and ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:101:- For metadata/dynamic-access entry mismatch: ask for investigation only when covered dynamic-access calls are at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count. Do not manually count or argue from metadata contents.\n./stats/mysql/mysql-connector-java/8.0.29/stats.json:8:          \"coveredCalls\" : 12,\n./stats/mysql/mysql-connector-java/8.0.29/stats.json:13:          \"coveredCalls\" : 2,\n./stats/mysql/mysql-connector-java/8.0.29/stats.json:18:      \"coveredCalls\" : 14,\n./stats/com.fasterxml/classmate/1.5.1/stats.json:8:          \"coveredCalls\" : 5,\n./stats/com.fasterxml/classmate/1.5.1/stats.json:13:      \"coveredCalls\" : 5,\n./stats/com.google.protobuf/protobuf-java-util/3.23.0/stats.json:8:          \"coveredCalls\" : 1,\n./stats/com.google.protobuf/protobuf-java-util/3.23.0/stats.json:13:      \"coveredCalls\" : 1,\n./stats/com.google.protobuf/